04937nam a22006615i 9780231554947DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20222022nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021060324  a97802315549477 a10.7312/sall203242doi  a(DE-B1597)638371  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aJQ3881b.S249 2022 7aPOL0590002bisacsh1 aSallam, Hesham, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aClassless Politics :bIslamist Movements, the Left, and Authoritarian Legacies in Egypt /cHesham Sallam. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aColumbia Studies in Middle East Politics00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgment -- tA Note on Transliteration -- tIntroduction. More Identity, Less Class: Paths to Classless Politics -- t1 Inheriting Nasser’s Debts: The Rise and Fall of the Nasserist Social Pact -- t2 Islamist Incorporation in the State of Science and Faith -- t3 Sadat’s Brothers: Islamist Incorporation and the Autonomous Path -- t4 Nasser’s Comrades: State Guardianship and the Dependent Path -- t5 Islamist Incorporation, National Identity, and the Left: A Tale of Two Comrades -- tConclusion. Reflections on the Legacies of Islamist Incorporation and the Post-Mubarak Politics -- tAppendix I. The Theoretical Argument, Key Concepts, and Central Assumptions -- tAppendix II. Critical Junctures and Path-Dependent Institutional Patterns -- tNote -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince the 1970s, the Egyptian state has embarked on a far-reaching and destabilizing project of economic liberalization, reneging on its commitments to social welfare. Despite widespread socioeconomic grievances stemming from these policies, class politics and battles over wealth redistribution have largely been sidelined from elite-led national politics. Instead, conflicts over identity have raged, as Islamist movements became increasingly prominent political players.Classless Politics offers a counterintuitive account of the relationship between neoliberal economics and Islamist politics in Egypt that sheds new light on the worldwide trend of “more identity, less class.” Hesham Sallam examines why Islamist movements have gained support at the expense of the left, even amid conflicts over the costs of economic reforms. Rather than highlighting the stagnancy of the left or the agility of Islamists, he pinpoints the historical legacies of authoritarian survival strategies. As the regime resorted to economic liberalization in the 1970s, it tacitly opened political space for Islamist movements to marginalize its leftist opponents. In the long run, this policy led to the fragmentation of opponents of economic reform, the increased salience of cultural conflicts within the left, and the restructuring of political life around questions of national and religious identity.Historically rich and theoretically insightful, this book demonstrates how the participation of Islamist groups shapes the politics of neoliberal reform and addresses why economic liberalization since the 1970s has contributed to the surge in culture wars around the world today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aIdentity politicszEgypt. 0aIslam and politicszEgypt. 0aPolitical participationzEgypt. 0aRight and left (Political science)zEgypt. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Middle Eastern.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311074966340uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/sall2032440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231554947423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/97802